1
00:00:00,133 --> 00:00:01,266
我先问你一个问题
Let me ask you a question first

2
00:00:01,566 --> 00:00:03,033
如果让你选一本书
If you had to pick one book

3
00:00:03,200 --> 00:00:06,366
能让普通人的认知水平提高一个量级
That could level up an ordinary person's thinking by an order of magnitude

4
00:00:06,566 --> 00:00:07,766
你会选哪本
Which one would you choose

5
00:00:07,900 --> 00:00:09,833
很多人会说国富论资本论
Many people would say The Wealth of Nations or Das Kapital

6
00:00:10,000 --> 00:00:12,200
但巴菲特自己开口推荐的
But Buffett personally recommended

7
00:00:12,400 --> 00:00:13,333
是另一本
A different one

8
00:00:13,566 --> 00:00:14,566
穷查理宝典
Poor Charlie's Almanack

9
00:00:14,733 --> 00:00:16,166
这本书的作者
The author of this book

10
00:00:16,333 --> 00:00:17,533
叫查理芒格
Is Charlie Munger

11
00:00:17,766 --> 00:00:18,866
巴菲特的搭档
Buffett's partner

12
00:00:19,133 --> 00:00:21,333
伯克希尔哈撒韦的副董事长
Vice Chairman of Berkshire Hathaway

13
00:00:21,833 --> 00:00:23,133
99岁去世前
Right up until he passed away at 99

14
00:00:23,366 --> 00:00:25,166
还在每天读书6小时
He was still reading 6 hours a day

15
00:00:25,333 --> 00:00:28,366
在2023年的股东大会上
At the 2023 shareholders meeting

16
00:00:28,533 --> 00:00:29,666
有人问芒格
Someone asked Munger

17
00:00:29,966 --> 00:00:31,766
普通人最大的错误是什么
What is the biggest mistake ordinary people make

18
00:00:31,900 --> 00:00:33,133
你猜他怎么答
Guess what he said

19
00:00:33,366 --> 00:00:34,333
不是没钱
It's not being broke

20
00:00:34,600 --> 00:00:35,666
不是没机会
It's not lacking opportunities

21
00:00:35,900 --> 00:00:37,066
不是没人脉
It's not having no connections

22
00:00:37,166 --> 00:00:37,966
他说
He said

23
00:00:38,300 --> 00:00:40,433
是拿着锤子看什么都是钉子
It's seeing every problem as a nail when all you have is a hammer

24
00:00:40,600 --> 00:00:41,400
什么意思
What does that mean

25
00:00:41,733 --> 00:00:44,066
就是你只会一种思维方式
It means you only know one way of thinking

26
00:00:44,233 --> 00:00:47,333
然后用它去解释这个世界上所有的问题
And you use it to explain every problem in the world

27
00:00:47,600 --> 00:00:49,966
这是一个100亿美金身家的老头
This is the final advice from a man worth 10 billion dollars

28
00:00:50,200 --> 00:00:51,733
留给我们的最后忠告
Left for the rest of us

29
00:00:51,966 --> 00:00:53,333
今天我用10分钟
Today I'll use 10 minutes

30
00:00:53,500 --> 00:00:56,800
把这本书最核心的3个思维工具讲给你听
To walk you through the 3 core thinking tools from this book

31
00:00:56,933 --> 00:00:58,033
这3个工具
These 3 tools

32
00:00:58,200 --> 00:00:59,633
你只要用上一个
If you put even one of them to use

33
00:00:59,966 --> 00:01:03,333
未来10年的人生决策就会跟现在完全不一样
Your life decisions over the next 10 years will be completely different

34
00:01:03,433 --> 00:01:04,800
回到芒格那句话
Back to what Munger said

35
00:01:05,033 --> 00:01:06,933
拿着锤子看什么都是钉子
To the man with a hammer everything looks like a nail

36
00:01:07,033 --> 00:01:08,400
这句话其实很扎心
This actually hits pretty hard

37
00:01:08,566 --> 00:01:09,866
我给你看几个例子
Let me show you some examples

38
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:11,800
你看看像不像自己身边的人
See if they remind you of people you know

39
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:12,833
有个朋友
There's a friend

40
00:01:13,366 --> 00:01:14,766
本科学心理学
Who studied psychology in college

41
00:01:14,933 --> 00:01:16,366
不管你跟他聊什么
No matter what you talk about with them

42
00:01:16,533 --> 00:01:17,733
经济不景气
The economy is bad

43
00:01:17,933 --> 00:01:18,966
夫妻吵架
A couple fighting

44
00:01:19,166 --> 00:01:20,533
孩子学习不好
A kid struggling in school

45
00:01:20,733 --> 00:01:21,833
公司倒闭
A company going under

46
00:01:22,000 --> 00:01:24,066
他都能给你绕到原生家庭上去
They'll twist it back to childhood family issues

47
00:01:24,200 --> 00:01:25,433
这就是一把锤子
That's one hammer

48
00:01:25,600 --> 00:01:26,666
还有一种朋友
Another type of friend

49
00:01:27,000 --> 00:01:28,066
搞IT出身
From an IT background

50
00:01:28,300 --> 00:01:29,733
不管你跟他聊什么
No matter what you bring up

51
00:01:29,966 --> 00:01:31,166
他都给你画流程图
They'll draw you a flowchart

52
00:01:31,400 --> 00:01:32,866
恋爱要画流程图
Dating needs a flowchart

53
00:01:33,033 --> 00:01:34,733
养孩子要画流程图
Raising kids needs a flowchart

54
00:01:34,966 --> 00:01:36,366
买菜要画流程图
Even grocery shopping needs a flowchart

55
00:01:36,600 --> 00:01:37,966
这也是一把锤子
That's another hammer

56
00:01:38,100 --> 00:01:39,633
最常见的一种
The most common type

57
00:01:39,900 --> 00:01:41,666
是只懂金钱的人
Is someone who only understands money

58
00:01:41,800 --> 00:01:43,666
什么事都换算成值多少钱
They convert everything into how much it's worth

59
00:01:43,966 --> 00:01:45,166
时间值多少钱
How much is time worth

60
00:01:45,333 --> 00:01:46,833
感情值多少钱
How much are feelings worth

61
00:01:47,100 --> 00:01:48,366
健康值多少钱
How much is health worth

62
00:01:48,533 --> 00:01:49,766
自由值多少钱
How much is freedom worth

63
00:01:49,933 --> 00:01:51,166
一切都被定价
Everything gets a price tag

64
00:01:51,366 --> 00:01:52,866
这同样是一把锤子
That's yet another hammer

65
00:01:53,033 --> 00:01:54,000
芒格说
Munger said

66
00:01:54,200 --> 00:01:55,833
绝大多数人的一生
Most people's entire lives

67
00:01:56,000 --> 00:01:58,366
就死在自己唯一的那把锤子上
Die on their single hammer

68
00:01:58,600 --> 00:01:59,533
为什么
Why

69
00:01:59,966 --> 00:02:01,600
因为人脑的本能是省力
Because the brain's instinct is to save energy

70
00:02:01,800 --> 00:02:03,433
学会一种思维方式
Learning one way of thinking

71
00:02:03,566 --> 00:02:05,233
已经费了好大力气
Already takes a lot of effort

72
00:02:05,433 --> 00:02:07,433
谁愿意为了解释一个新问题
Who wants to learn a whole new way of thinking

73
00:02:07,900 --> 00:02:10,133
再去学一种新的思维方式
Just to explain a new problem

74
00:02:10,333 --> 00:02:11,366
太累了
That's exhausting

75
00:02:11,500 --> 00:02:13,400
所以大多数人这一辈子
So most people go through their whole lives

76
00:02:13,600 --> 00:02:16,766
就用一两种思维去硬套所有问题
Force-fitting one or two mental models onto every problem

77
00:02:17,000 --> 00:02:20,000
然后在该用经济学的时候用心理学
Using psychology when economics is called for

78
00:02:20,133 --> 00:02:22,066
该用心理学的时候用法律
Using law when psychology is needed

79
00:02:22,233 --> 00:02:24,533
该用统计学的时候用直觉
Going with gut feeling when statistics should apply

80
00:02:24,700 --> 00:02:26,633
最后撞得头破血流
And end up crashing and burning

81
00:02:26,833 --> 00:02:28,400
还以为是命不好
Blaming it on bad luck

82
00:02:28,600 --> 00:02:29,933
你回头看看自己
Look back at yourself

83
00:02:30,200 --> 00:02:31,533
你过去5年
Over the past 5 years

84
00:02:31,766 --> 00:02:34,166
是不是也只用了两三把锤子
Haven't you also been using just two or three hammers

85
00:02:34,233 --> 00:02:35,033
注意听
Listen carefully

86
00:02:35,200 --> 00:02:38,066
这里讲一个让芒格成为芒格的核心方法
Here's the core method that made Munger who he was

87
00:02:38,200 --> 00:02:40,033
它叫多元思维模型
It's called the latticework of mental models

88
00:02:40,166 --> 00:02:40,966
什么意思
What does that mean

89
00:02:41,200 --> 00:02:42,066
芒格说
Munger said

90
00:02:42,433 --> 00:02:45,200
你脑子里至少要有100个思维模型
You need at least 100 mental models in your head

91
00:02:45,366 --> 00:02:46,733
来自不同学科
From different disciplines

92
00:02:47,000 --> 00:02:47,966
数学的
Mathematics

93
00:02:48,200 --> 00:02:49,033
物理的
Physics

94
00:02:49,366 --> 00:02:50,266
生物的
Biology

95
00:02:50,500 --> 00:02:51,533
心理学的
Psychology

96
00:02:51,766 --> 00:02:52,766
经济学的
Economics

97
00:02:53,033 --> 00:02:53,933
历史的
History

98
00:02:54,233 --> 00:02:55,166
化学的
Chemistry

99
00:02:55,366 --> 00:02:56,400
不同领域
Different fields

100
00:02:56,566 --> 00:02:57,566
不同视角
Different perspectives

101
00:02:57,733 --> 00:02:58,633
互相补充
Complementing each other

102
00:02:58,833 --> 00:02:59,966
遇到一个新问题
When you face a new problem

103
00:03:00,300 --> 00:03:02,666
不是用唯一的那把锤子去敲
You don't just swing your one hammer

104
00:03:02,966 --> 00:03:05,566
而是把这100个模型一个个拿出来比对
Instead you pull out these 100 models one by one and compare

105
00:03:05,733 --> 00:03:06,533
这事儿
Which one of these

106
00:03:06,833 --> 00:03:08,133
更像哪一个
Does this problem resemble the most

107
00:03:08,300 --> 00:03:10,466
我给你举个芒格自己用过的例子
Let me give you an example Munger used himself

108
00:03:10,633 --> 00:03:12,833
可口可乐为什么这么值钱
Why is Coca-Cola so valuable

109
00:03:13,000 --> 00:03:14,266
如果只用经济学
If you only use economics

110
00:03:14,433 --> 00:03:16,266
你会说是因为它有定价权
You'd say it's because of pricing power

111
00:03:16,566 --> 00:03:17,733
有规模效应
And economies of scale

112
00:03:17,833 --> 00:03:19,366
但芒格不是这么想的
But Munger didn't think that way

113
00:03:19,500 --> 00:03:22,033
他用了4个学科的模型同时分析
He analyzed it using models from 4 disciplines at once

114
00:03:22,233 --> 00:03:23,133
第一个
Number one

115
00:03:23,400 --> 00:03:25,000
心理学的条件反射
Classical conditioning from psychology

116
00:03:25,200 --> 00:03:26,166
红色罐子
The red can

117
00:03:26,366 --> 00:03:27,600
开瓶气泡声
The fizz when you open it

118
00:03:27,800 --> 00:03:28,933
冰凉口感
The cold refreshing taste

119
00:03:29,100 --> 00:03:30,733
让人形成自动联想
Creates automatic associations in people's minds

120
00:03:30,933 --> 00:03:31,866
第二个
Number two

121
00:03:32,133 --> 00:03:34,233
生物学的进化偏好
Evolutionary preference from biology

122
00:03:34,400 --> 00:03:36,866
人类天生喜欢甜和咖啡因
Humans are hardwired to love sugar and caffeine

123
00:03:37,100 --> 00:03:38,600
这是基因写好的
It's coded into our genes

124
00:03:38,733 --> 00:03:39,766
第三个
Number three

125
00:03:40,000 --> 00:03:41,866
经济学的网络效应
Network effects from economics

126
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:43,600
可口可乐越普及
The more widespread Coca-Cola becomes

127
00:03:43,833 --> 00:03:45,200
越多人模仿
The more people imitate it

128
00:03:45,400 --> 00:03:46,633
全球都在喝
The whole world is drinking it

129
00:03:46,833 --> 00:03:47,866
第四个
Number four

130
00:03:48,100 --> 00:03:49,633
社会学的身份认同
Social identity from sociology

131
00:03:49,900 --> 00:03:53,233
可乐变成一种美国生活方式的象征
Coke has become a symbol of the American lifestyle

132
00:03:53,433 --> 00:03:54,966
4个模型叠在一起
Layer these 4 models together

133
00:03:55,133 --> 00:03:56,166
他得出结论
And he reached his conclusion

134
00:03:56,333 --> 00:04:00,000
这是一个跨越100年都很难被替代的资产
This is an asset that's nearly impossible to replace even over 100 years

135
00:04:00,166 --> 00:04:04,400
然后他和巴菲特1988年重仓买入可口可乐
Then in 1988 he and Buffett went heavy on Coca-Cola stock

136
00:04:04,600 --> 00:04:05,933
到现在赚了多少
How much have they made since

137
00:04:06,166 --> 00:04:07,633
超过200亿美元
Over 20 billion dollars

138
00:04:07,700 --> 00:04:08,500
你看
You see

139
00:04:08,700 --> 00:04:10,966
多元思维模型不是装逼
A latticework of mental models isn't just showing off

140
00:04:11,200 --> 00:04:12,133
是用它
With it

141
00:04:12,433 --> 00:04:14,066
你能比别人看得更深
You can see deeper than others

142
00:04:14,233 --> 00:04:15,033
更早
Earlier

143
00:04:15,300 --> 00:04:16,100
更准
And more accurately

144
00:04:16,166 --> 00:04:18,000
我再给你一个生活里的例子
Let me give you another real-life example

145
00:04:18,133 --> 00:04:19,466
你身边有没有人
Do you know someone

146
00:04:19,633 --> 00:04:21,433
谈了好几次恋爱都谈不下去
Who's had multiple relationships but none of them worked out

147
00:04:21,566 --> 00:04:23,333
如果你只用心理学解释
If you only explain it with psychology

148
00:04:23,400 --> 00:04:25,000
你说他原生家庭有问题
You'd say their family of origin is the issue

149
00:04:25,300 --> 00:04:28,333
但芒格的方法是叠加多个学科
But Munger's approach is to layer multiple disciplines

150
00:04:28,533 --> 00:04:29,400
经济学
Economics

151
00:04:29,566 --> 00:04:31,733
他为这段关系投入的成本
How much they've invested in the relationship

152
00:04:31,900 --> 00:04:33,433
是不是远低于对方
Is it far less than what the other person put in

153
00:04:33,633 --> 00:04:35,200
沉没成本不平衡
Unbalanced sunk costs

154
00:04:35,400 --> 00:04:36,333
社会学
Sociology

155
00:04:36,433 --> 00:04:38,833
他的朋友圈和对方差距太大
Their social circles are too far apart

156
00:04:39,033 --> 00:04:41,033
社会支持系统冲突
Conflict in social support systems

157
00:04:41,200 --> 00:04:42,566
进化心理学
Evolutionary psychology

158
00:04:42,733 --> 00:04:46,866
他可能在选择一个跟自己生育策略不匹配的对象
They might be choosing a partner who doesn't match their reproductive strategy

159
00:04:47,100 --> 00:04:48,233
行为经济学
Behavioral economics

160
00:04:48,433 --> 00:04:51,200
他每次决定都靠当下情绪
Every decision they make is driven by the emotion of the moment

161
00:04:51,500 --> 00:04:53,066
没有用理性分析
No rational analysis involved

162
00:04:53,333 --> 00:04:54,800
4个角度一叠加
Layer these 4 angles together

163
00:04:55,033 --> 00:04:56,533
问题立刻立体
And the problem instantly becomes three-dimensional

164
00:04:56,733 --> 00:05:00,133
解决方案也不再是单一的去做心理咨询
The solution is no longer just going to therapy

165
00:05:00,300 --> 00:05:02,566
而是从4个层面同时调整
But adjusting on all 4 fronts at the same time

166
00:05:02,700 --> 00:05:04,866
这就是多元思维模型的威力
That is the power of the latticework of mental models

167
00:05:05,033 --> 00:05:06,833
它不是让你变得博学
It doesn't make you a know-it-all

168
00:05:07,033 --> 00:05:08,533
是让你变得准确
It makes you accurate

169
00:05:08,633 --> 00:05:09,566
回到主线
Back to the main topic

170
00:05:09,733 --> 00:05:11,833
芒格在书里反复强调一个词
Munger repeatedly emphasizes one phrase in the book

171
00:05:12,033 --> 00:05:12,866
倒过来想
Invert always

172
00:05:13,300 --> 00:05:14,333
always invert
always invert

173
00:05:14,566 --> 00:05:16,033
什么叫倒过来想
What does invert always mean

174
00:05:16,200 --> 00:05:18,066
我给你看一个最经典的例子
Let me show you the most classic example

175
00:05:18,233 --> 00:05:19,666
1985年
In 1985

176
00:05:19,933 --> 00:05:22,333
可口可乐的CEO问芒格
The CEO of Coca-Cola asked Munger

177
00:05:22,600 --> 00:05:25,433
怎么让可口可乐成为更伟大的公司
How to make Coca-Cola an even greater company

178
00:05:25,600 --> 00:05:26,566
如果是你
If it were you

179
00:05:26,900 --> 00:05:27,966
你会怎么答
How would you answer

180
00:05:28,300 --> 00:05:29,833
大多数人会说
Most people would say

181
00:05:30,100 --> 00:05:31,266
投更多广告
Spend more on advertising

182
00:05:31,500 --> 00:05:32,733
研发新口味
Develop new flavors

183
00:05:32,900 --> 00:05:34,266
扩张到更多国家
Expand to more countries

184
00:05:34,500 --> 00:05:35,633
芒格反过来问
Munger flipped the question around

185
00:05:35,833 --> 00:05:37,966
怎么样才能毁掉可口可乐
How could you destroy Coca-Cola

186
00:05:38,166 --> 00:05:39,333
他列了10条
He listed 10 things

187
00:05:39,500 --> 00:05:41,666
让它失去那种独一无二的口感
Lose that one-of-a-kind taste

188
00:05:41,800 --> 00:05:43,733
让它的瓶装合作伙伴破产
Drive its bottling partners into bankruptcy

189
00:05:43,933 --> 00:05:47,166
让它的品牌跟某种政治丑闻绑定
Tie the brand to some political scandal

190
00:05:47,366 --> 00:05:49,933
让健康趋势对它不利但它不去应对
Let health trends turn against it without responding

191
00:05:50,100 --> 00:05:53,366
让某次广告冒犯了某个种族群体
Have an ad offend some ethnic group

192
00:05:53,566 --> 00:05:54,566
列完之后
After listing them all

193
00:05:54,800 --> 00:05:56,133
他对CEO说
He told the CEO

194
00:05:56,366 --> 00:05:57,833
把这10条做反
Do the opposite of all 10

195
00:05:58,000 --> 00:06:00,000
你就找到了所有要避免的事
And you've found everything to avoid

196
00:06:00,300 --> 00:06:01,200
剩下的
The rest

197
00:06:01,400 --> 00:06:03,466
就是怎么不做这些事
Is simply not doing those things

198
00:06:03,700 --> 00:06:05,033
这就是逆向思维
This is inversion thinking

199
00:06:05,166 --> 00:06:06,266
它的核心是
The core idea is

200
00:06:06,566 --> 00:06:07,966
不去想怎么成功
Don't think about how to succeed

201
00:06:08,166 --> 00:06:09,666
而是想怎么必败
